Title = {AutoMind: Automated Insight Discovery via Multi-Agent Navigation},
Journal = {IEEE ACCESS},
Year = {2026},
Volume = {14},
Pages = {23936-23955},
Abstract = {The proliferation of data across all sectors has created a significant
   ``competency gap{''}, where domain experts in fields like business,
   healthcare, and education possess critical contextual knowledge but lack
   the technical skills for advanced data analysis. This bottleneck
   prevents organizations from fully capitalizing on their data assets. To
   bridge this gap, this paper introduces AutoMind, a novel framework that
   automates the end-to-end data analysis pipeline for non-technical users.
   Leveraging a sophisticated multi-agent architecture powered by Large
   Language Models (LLMs), AutoMind translates high-level, natural language
   goals into comprehensive analytical workflows. The system employs an
   orchestrator-worker pattern, where a central agent devises a plan and
   delegates tasks, from data profiling and cleaning to modeling and
   insight generation, to a team of specialized agents. A key innovation is
   AutoMind's ability to automatically detect and apply appropriate
   statistical methods for complex data structures, such as hierarchical
   data, which are common across many domains but are mishandled by
   traditional automated tools. Through empirical evaluation on diverse
   real-world datasets from business, healthcare and education, we
   demonstrate that AutoMind produces results competitive with, and in some
   cases superior to, manual analysis by human experts. Our framework
   represents a significant step toward democratizing data science,
   empowering domain experts to unlock critical insights independently.},
